          "body": "The pivot of the entire psalm — and, as Paul recognized, of the entire Old Testament's doctrine of justification — is verse 2: 'Do not enter into judgment with Your servant, for in Your sight no man living is righteous.' This is not rhetorical self-deprecation. It is a categorical theological statement: brought to the bar of God's own standard, no living human being can produce a righteousness that satisfies the divine assessment. The appeal, therefore, must be grounded entirely in God's own faithfulness (emunah) and righteousness (tsedaqah) — named in verse 1. David enters the psalm stripped of every personal claim. His only standing is the covenant identity 'Your servant' (eved, v.2). Paul quotes this verse in both Romans 3:20 and Galatians 2:16 to demolish the doctrine of justification by works of the law. The psalm pre-codes the gospel: the rescue that comes in verses 7-12 is not earned by the one who receives it; it flows from the One who gives it. Calvin notes: 'David makes no mention of his own righteousness as a ground of confidence; he rests everything on the grace of God' (Commentary on Psalm 143)."
