          "body": "Verses 3-4 give the most condensed description of spiritual and psychological devastation in the Psalter. Three perfect-tense verbs describe completed acts of the enemy: pursued the soul (radaph), crushed life to the ground (dakah), made David dwell in dark places (machshakh). Each verb intensifies the previous: pursuit yields to being ground down; being ground down yields to entombment. The comparison to 'those who have long been dead' (olam) is not exaggeration — it is precision. The darkness of the dead is total, irreversible, beyond human remedy. Then verse 4 turns inward: the spirit (ruach) overwhelms and the heart (lev) is appalled (shamem — the word used of desolated land, Ezekiel 6:4). The outer assault has produced inner desolation. This sequence — external persecution generating internal devastation — is the psychological pattern the church has called 'the dark night of the soul' (John of the Cross). The psalm does not paper over it; it inhabits it completely before offering any relief, because the depth of the cry must match the depth of the need."
